s://globalnews.ca/news/6666046/no-spring-election-saskatchewan-premier-scott-moe-coronavirus/|title=No spring election: Saskatchewan Premier Scott Moe|website=Global News|access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 13, 2020, following the second presumptive case in the province, the Saskatchewan government announced restrictions on gatherings of more than 250 people in contiguous indoor space, as well as gatherings of more than 50 people if they include participants who had recently travelled internationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-virtual-appointments-for-patients/|title=COVID-19 live updates: Second presumptive case found in Sask.|website=Regina Leader Post|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314193203/https://leaderpost.com/news/saskatchewan/covid-19-live-updates-virtual-appointments-for-patients/|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/gatherings-of-250-people-or-more-banned-in-sask-as-second-presumptive-covid-19-case-confirmed-1.4852364|title=Gatherings of 250 people or more banned in Sask. as second presumptive COVID-19 case confirmed|date=March 13, 2020|website=CTV News Saskatoon|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313211404/https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/gatherings-of-250-people-or-more-banned-in-sask-as-second-presumptive-covid-19-case-confirmed-1.4852364|archive-date=March 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Exceptions are permitted for retail shops.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6684078/hospitals-casinos-coronavirus-prevention-saskatchewan/|title=Hospital visitor restrictions, casinos closing part of coronavirus prevention|website=Global News|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name = Sask-update-March13>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/province-increased-measures-covid-19-update-1.5497233 |title=\"Saskatchewan officials provide COVID update after second presumptive casecfound in province\", CBC News, March 13, 2020. |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314132339/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/province-increased-measures-covid-19-update-1.5497233 |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> An exception for faith-based organizations was removed March 16.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs an employer, the government of Saskatchewan has sharply reduced inter-provincial and international travel on government business by any provincial employees. It has also provided that provincial employees who have travelled outside the country, whether on government business or personal travel, must self-isolate for fourteen days upon their return.<ref name=Sask-update-March13/>\n\nOn March 17, 2020, the government announced that it was delaying the introduction of the provincial budget, because the government revenue forecasts underlying it were no longer reliable, in light of the current situation.  The Government would announce the planned spending, including for the health care sector, which would see an increase in funding.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/sask-gov-budget-postponed-1.5500607 |title=\"Sask. government postpones full budget, will release spending plans Wednesday\", Adam Hunter, CBC News, March 17, 2020. |access-date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321175144/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/sask-gov-budget-postponed-1.5500607 |archive-date=March 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The same day, the Legislature passed amendments to provincial employment law, to provide unpaid job security to employees during the pandemic.  The amendments passed with the support of both parties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-sask-introduces-unpaid-job-protected-leave-1.4856960|title=COVID-19: Sask. introduces unpaid job protected leave|first=Michaela|last=Solomon|date=March 17, 2020|website=CTV News|access-date=March 23, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327064802/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-sask-introduces-unpaid-job-protected-leave-1.4856960|archive-date=March 27, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The next day, the Legislature adjourned its spring sitting, with the consent of the Opposition.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/legislature-adjourned-1.5503813 |title=\"Saskatchewan legislative sitting abruptly adjourned amid COVID-19 pandemic\", Adam Hunter, CBC News, March 19, 2020. |access-date=March 23, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321144331/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/legislature-adjourned-1.5503813 |archive-date=March 21, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===State of emergency===\nSaskatchewan declared a state of emergency on March 18, which included a ban of all gatherings of 50 people or more, restricting capacity of restaurants and similar venues to a maximum of 50 or half their normal capacity (whichever was lower), mandatory closure of all fitness facilities, casinos, and bingo halls, shifting all provincial government entities and crown corporations to remote work on March 23, authorizing the [[Saskatchewan Health Authority]] to \"redeploy nurses and other staff and ensure medical supplies and personal protective equipment are available when needed and reduce risk of further exposure to our care providers and patients\", and advising against non-essential travel outside of the province.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-sask-declares-state-of-emergency-additional-measures-after-announcing-8-new-cases-1.4858436|title=COVID-19: Sask. declares state of emergency, additional measures, after announcing 8 new cases|date=March 18, 2020|website=CTV News Regina|access-date=March 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319004333/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-sask-declares-state-of-emergency-additional-measures-after-announcing-8-new-cases-1.4858436|archive-date=March 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cjme.com/2020/03/14/new-restrictions-announced-as-sask-covid-19-cases-rise-to-6/|title=New restrictions announced as Sask. COVID-19 cases rise to 6|website=[[CJME|980 CJME]]|access-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6698018/saskatchewan-state-of-emergency-covid-19-coronavirus/|title=Saskatchewan declares state of emergency as coronavirus concerns grow|website=Global News|access-date=March 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318221045/https://globalnews.ca/news/6698018/saskatchewan-state-of-emergency-covid-19-coronavirus/|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nOn March 20, Premier Moe signed an order allowing regulations issued pursuant to the state of emergency, whether by the government or the chief medical officer, to be enforceable under provincial law. Law enforcement agencies, including the [[RCMP]], were granted the authority to enforce these measures under penalties of fines or arrest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6710474/saskatchewan-order-enforcing-measures-protecting-against-covid-19/|title=Saskatchewan premier signs order enforcing measures protecting against spread of COVID-19|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321135259/https://globalnews.ca/news/6710474/saskatchewan-order-enforcing-measures-protecting-against-covid-19/|archive-date=March 21, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  The government subsequently announced that residents returning from any international travel, and those identified as contacts of someone who contracted the virus, would be required by law to self-isolate for 14 days, with those breaking quarantine subject to a $2,000 fine.<ref name=\":10\" /> Essential travellers such as working crews, transport workers and health care workers were exempt.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/mandatory-self-isolation-after-travel-now-law-as-sask-announces-6-more-covid-19-cases-1.4861706|title=Mandatory self-isolation after travel now law as Sask. announces 6 more COVID-19 cases|date=March 20, 2020|website=CTV News Regina|url-status=live|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320224446/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/mandatory-self-isolation-after-travel-now-law-as-sask-announces-6-more-covid-19-cases-1.4861706|archive-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Premier Moe cited concerns over those not following its previous recommendations for self-isolation as justification.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/this-is-now-the-law-here-are-the-new-measures-announced-in-sask-1.4861951|title='This is now the law': Here are the new measures announced in Sask.|last=|first=|date=2020-03-20|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321141614/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/this-is-now-the-law-here-are-the-new-measures-announced-in-sask-1.4861951|archive-date=March 21, 2020|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\nAdditional restrictions were also announced on March 20, to take effect on March 23.  All restaurants, bars, and nightclubs were restricted to take-out service only (bars and nightclubs could only do so if customers were capable of maintaining a distance of 2 metres from each other). All art galleries, museums, and other recreational, entertainment, and personal service facilities were ordered closed, and certain types of medical clinics (chiropractors, dentists, optometrists, [[Podiatrist|podiatrists]], and registered massage therapists) were restricted to non-elective appointments only. All gatherings of 25 people or more were prohibited unless all patrons were capable of maintaining a distance of 2 metres from each other.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/saskatchewan-coronavirus-1.5504240|title=COVID-19 in Sask: Premier threatens international travellers who don't self-isolate with arrest, fines|last=Quenneville|first=Guy|date=March 20, 2020|website=|url-status=live|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321143011/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatoon/saskatchewan-coronavirus-1.5504240|archive-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOn March 25, Saskatchewan announced that beginning March 26, all gatherings must be limited to 10 people, and all businesses not considered essential by the province were required to close to the public.  Examples of \"non-allowable business services\" included but were not limited to ATV, boat, and snowmobile retailers, clothing, shoe, accessory, and jewellery stores, electronics, entertainment, and toy stores, flower shops, book, gift, and stationary stores, sporting goods stores, pawn shops, and travel agencies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/14-new-covid-19-cases-in-sask-as-province-limits-gatherings-to-10-1.4867855|title=14 new COVID-19 cases in Sask. as province limits gatherings to 10|date=2020-03-25|website=Regina|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325205555/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/14-new-covid-19-cases-in-sask-as-province-limits-gatherings-to-10-1.4867855|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saskatchewan.ca/government/news-and-media/2020/march/25/allowable-business-services|title=Government Clarifies Allowable Business Services, Limits Gatherings To 10 Person Maximum|website=Government of Saskatchewan|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325205555/https://www.saskatchewan.ca/government/news-and-media/2020/march/25/allowable-business-services|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Alert Ready]] has been activated twice to provide notice of the self-isolation order, first on March 20,<ref name=\":10\" /> and again March 27.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.620ckrm.com/2020/03/27/emergency-alert-issued-by-province-of-saskatchewan-due-to-covid-19/|title=Emergency alert for travelers issued by province of Saskatchewan due to COVID-19|last=McNally|first=Ryan|date=|website=620 CKRM|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n== Local responses ==\nOn March 18, a Sangster's health store in [[Lawson Heights, Saskatoon]] was closed after multiple visits by a customer who stated that she had recently returned from international travel to [[Hawaii]], and that multiple passengers on the flight had felt ill. The store's local owner criticized the customer for breaking recommended self-quarantine, even though she had displayed no symptoms herself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-after-brush-with-irresponsible-customer-saskatoon-business-closes-to-in-person-traffic-1.4859725|title=COVID-19: After brush with 'irresponsible' customer Saskatoon business closes to in-person traffic|last=Lynn|first=Josh|date=2020-03-19|website=Saskatoon|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324195922/https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-after-brush-with-irresponsible-customer-saskatoon-business-closes-to-in-person-traffic-1.4859725|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 20, [[Regina Transit]] and [[Saskatoon Transit]] suspended fares for all bus service, but with reduced service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-saskatoon-transit-for-essential-travel-only-city-says-1.4865940|title=COVID-19: Saskatoon Transit for 'essential travel only' city says|last=Lynn|first=Josh|date=2020-03-24|website=Saskatoon|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325160337/https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-saskatoon-transit-for-essential-travel-only-city-says-1.4865940|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6701505/saskatoon-city-council-covid-19-coronavirus/|title=Saskatoon city council passes special measures to deal with COVID-19 pandemic|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324195920/https://globalnews.ca/news/6701505/saskatoon-city-council-covid-19-coronavirus/|archive-date=March 24, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cjme.com/2020/03/20/628329/|title=Regina Transit to keep operating, but with changes|date=|website=980 CJME|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Local orders with measures contrary to provincial measures ===\nThe municipal governments of [[Gravelbourg]] and Regina declared their own states of emergency with stricter restrictions than those enforced by the province. Regina announced an intent to ban all public meetings larger than 5 people or more (outside of home, workplaces, or as part of essential services), and order the closure of retail stores in specific categories to in-person shopping (including clothing, furniture, games, sporting goods, and toys) effective March 23.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6708095/regina-state-of-emergency/|title=Regina declares local state of emergency, limiting size of gatherings|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322203551/https://globalnews.ca/news/6708095/regina-state-of-emergency/|archive-date=March 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>  Gravelbourg similarly ordered that all businesses be closed to the public for 14 days (delivery and curbside pickup would still be allowed), and that only a maximum of five employees could be in a building at any one time (with planned special operating requirements for the local [[Federated Co-operatives|Co-op]] store).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/here-s-what-the-state-of-local-emergency-in-gravelbourg-sask-means-for-residents-1.4863507|title=Here's what the state of local emergency in Gravelbourg, Sask. means for residents|last=|first=|date=2020-03-22|website=CTV News Regina|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323135828/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/here-s-what-the-state-of-local-emergency-in-gravelbourg-sask-means-for-residents-1.4863507|archive-date=March 23, 2020|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>  \n\nOn March 22, the province stated that it would take steps to ensure that its emergency measures maintain precedence over municipal orders that include \"contrary standards\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6716266/coronavirus-saskatchewan-municipalities-regulations/|title=Saskatchewan municipalities can\u2019t make up their own coronavirus regulations: province|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323135247/https://globalnews.ca/news/6716266/coronavirus-saskatchewan-municipalities-regulations/|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Minister of Government Relations Lori Carr explained that \"during this time of great uncertainty, it is of the utmost importance that we provide certainty to Saskatchewan residents and make every effort to minimize confusion\", and cited Regina's attempts to close retail stores as an example of a restriction where provincial decisions take precedence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/here-s-some-clarification-on-the-conflicting-orders-made-by-the-province-and-the-city-of-regina-1.4863546|title=Here's some clarification on the conflicting orders made by the province and the City of Regina|date=2020-03-22|website=Regina|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323135124/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/here-s-some-clarification-on-the-conflicting-orders-made-by-the-province-and-the-city-of-regina-1.4863546|archive-date=March 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/government-clarity-cregina-emergency-order-1.5506234|title=Government to review, cancel City of Regina emergency order|last=Eneas|first=Brian|date=2020-03-22|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323151142/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/government-clarity-cregina-emergency-order-1.5506234|archive-date=March 23, 2020|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n==Regional distribution==\n\nThe following table summarises the number of persons with COVID-2 in Saskatchewan as of April 4, 2020.<ref name = \"saskcovid19\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!Public Health Region\n!Cases\n!Inpatient Hospitalisation\n!ICU Hospitalisations\n!Recovered\n!Deaths\n|-\n| [[Saskatoon]]\n| <center>112</center>\n| <center>3</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>24</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n|-\n| [[Regina]]\n| <center>50</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>12</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n|-\n| North\n| <center>43</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>14</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n|-\n| Central (excluding Saskatoon)\n| <center>10</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n| <center>1</center>\n|-\n| South (excluding Regina)\n| <center>13</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>2</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n|-\n| Far North\n| <center>3</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n| <center>2</center>\n| <center>0</center>\n|- class=\"sort-bottom\"\n| '''Total'''\n| <center>'''231'''</center>\n| <center>'''3'''</center>\n| <center>'''1'''</center>\n| <center>'''55'''</center>\n| <center>'''3'''</center>\n|-\n|}\n\n==School closures==\nThe [[University of Regina]] and [[University of Saskatchewan]] voluntarily suspended in-person classes on March 16, and switched to online courses for the remainder of the semester.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/university-of-regina-suspends-classes-amid-covid-19-concerns-1.4852655|title=University of Regina suspends classes amid COVID-19 concerns|last=Ellis|first=Brendan|date=March 13, 2020|website=CTV News Regina|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314225820/https://regina.ctvnews.ca/university-of-regina-suspends-classes-amid-covid-19-concerns-1.4852655|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-concerns-prompt-u-of-s-to-temporarily-suspend-class-will-move-courses-online-1.4852879|title=COVID-19 concerns prompt U of S to temporarily suspend class, will move courses online|date=March 13, 2020|website=CTV News Saskatoon|access-date=March 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314133901/https://saskatoon.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-concerns-prompt-u-of-s-to-temporarily-suspend-class-will-move-courses-online-1.4852879|archive-date=March 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 16, the province announced that all public schools would \"wind down\" over the week, and close indefinitely on March 20. No academic penalties would be  issued for students that do not attend school during the week of March 20, final grades will be issued based on existing progress, and eligible Grade 12 students will be able to graduate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://regina.ctvnews.ca/sask-schools-closing-effective-march-20-over-covid-19-concerns-1.4854588|title=Sask. schools closing effective March 20 over COVID-19 concerns|date=March 16, 2020|website=CTV News Regina|url-status=live|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6683648/schools-saskatchewan-closing-covid-19-coronavirus/|title=Public schools in Saskatchewan closing amid coronavirus concerns|website=Global News|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>  Day cares have been capped at 8 children per teacher.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada by province or territory|Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:2020 in Saskatchewan|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "JohnnyMyself", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTimeline:Fix my incorrectly nested braces.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Saskatchewan"}
{"title_page": "Anaang people", "text_new": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Anaang\n| total = 2.6 million\n| total_year = 2015\n| total_ref = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/anw|title=Anaang|website=[[Ethnologue]]|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n| regions = [[Akwa Ibom State]] ([[Nigeria]])\n| languages = [[Anaang language|Anaang]]\n| religions = [[Christianity]] and [[Paganism]]\n| related_groups = [[Ibibio people|Ibibio]], [[Efik people|Efik]]\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\nThe '''Anaang''' (also spelled '''Annang''') are a [[Nigeria|Southern Nigerian]] ethnic group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipobinusa.org/ourstory|title=Our Story|website=Indigenous People of Biafra USA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> whose land is primarily within 8 of the present 31 [[Akwa Ibom State#Administrative areas|local government areas]] in [[Akwa Ibom State]]: [[Abak]], [[Essien Udim]], [[Etim Ekpo]], [[Ika, Nigeria|Ika]], [[Ikot Ekpene]], [[Obot Akara]], [[Oruk Anam]], [[Ukanafun]] in [[Akwa Ibom State]], and part of [[Obi Ngwa]]. They were formerly located in the former [[Abak]] and [[Ikot Ekpene]] Divisions of the Anaang Province, as well as part of the former [[Opobo]] Division of [[Uyo]] Province, in the former Eastern Region of Nigeria. The proper name for the [[Ika people|Ika]] of [[Akwa Ibom]] is [[Ika-Annang]].  Based on 2018 estimates, there are about 4 million Annang speakers in Akwa Ibom and over a million speakers living outside of the state including Nigeria. Annang natives are known to be fearless at heart, truthful and honest.\n\n==Location==\nThe Anaang people are located in South [[Nigeria]] and specifically [[Akwa Ibom State]] and [[Cross River State]].  The political capital of the Anaang people is Ikot Ekpene Local Government Area. \n\n==Culture==\nAnaang society is [[patriarchal]]. Individuals locate their place in the social world from the ''Ilip'', literally translated as \"womb\". Thus a brother/sister from the same ''Ilip'' means that they can trace their origin to the same mother or father. Those who can so trace their ancestry to the same parents form ''Ufok'' (literally a house or compound). Several ''ufoks'' make up ''Ekpuks'' or [[extended family]] and several ''Ekpuks'' (extended families) make up \"Ilung\" (meaning village) and several villages make up the \"''abie''\" or clan. This is in many ways similar to the system used by other [[Biafra|Biafran]] peoples but more centralized<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Warrant_Chiefs_indirect_rule_in_sout.html?id=yYoKAQAAIAAJ|title=The Warrant Chiefs: indirect rule in southeastern Nigeria, 1891-1929|last=Afigbo|first=Adiele Eberechukwu|date=1972|publisher=Longman|language=en}}</ref>.\n\nLeadership at the family, lineage, village, or clan level remains the prerogative of the men, and lineage ties extends to women even after marriage. There are many societies and associations (''Ulim'' also called \"udim\") for men and women which are very important in traditional village life. Individuals are measured by both the number and types of memberships in ''Ulim'' and by the achievements of one or more ''Ulims''.  Governance is done by elderly males who act as the legislative arm called Afe Ichong, directed by the ''Abong Ichong'' (Village Chief and Clan Chief) who is the head and the chief executive but without the authority beyond what the ''Afe Ichong'' gives. A chief can be appointed by the ''Afe'' or can be an inherited office. \n\nThe Anang speak the [[Annang language]] and perform a masquerade after the yam harvest to mark the visit of ancestral spirits, or ''ekpo''. This is also the name of a men's associations that once had great influence among Ibibio groups. The Anang carve masks with grotesque features, known as ''iliok'', which are considered dangerous and may only be viewed by members of the ''ekpo''. Other masks embody the beautiful spirit, or ''mfon''.<ref name=\"masks\">{{Cite book|last1=Hahner-Herzog |first1=Iris |last2=Kecsk\u00e9si |first2=Maria |last3=Vajda |first3=L\u00e1szl\u00f3 |date=1998|title=African masks from the Barbier-Mueller Collection, Geneva|publisher=Prestel|location=Munich|isbn=978-3-7913-1806-6}}</ref>\n\nThe strength of any individual, family (or group for that matter) is typically based upon a consensus of the village or clan through this complex social system.  In all this, Anang women are not completely subordinate to men.  Instead Anaang women are partners and leaders in many aspects of Anaang tradition, including serving as female chief priests \"Abia Iyong\" in the Iyong cult or as healers in the healing cults.  The first-born female known as ''Aliaha'' is important and commands respect in the family and lineage.  Some traditions hold that a woman's first birth should take place in her mother's compound.  Women's organizations such as \"abi-de\" and \"Nyaama\", and \"Isong Iban\"  play important roles in giving the women voice and status in society. There are no traditional or cultural barriers that prevent women from attaining high offices or positions.\n\nAnaangs value the ability to speak well and oratory ability using [[proverb]]s is highly desirable, especially among the leaders. The American anthropologist, [[Peter Farb]], stated that the name \"Anaang\" among this group means \"they who speak well\". An individual who has the gift of eloquent speech is often complimented as ''Akwo Anaang'', meaning the \"Man of Anaang\".<ref>Farb, P. (1974) Word Play: What Happens when People Talk. New York. Alfred Knopf Publishers {{ISBN|0-679-73408-2}}.</ref>\n\n===Fattening room===\nThe fattening room is traditionally where virgin adolescent girls were fattened up in preparation for marriage. A fattening room girl is known as a ''mbobo''. This was an occasion for a major village celebration. As part of her preparation for marriage the girl was also instructed on how to be a wife. She would spend her time in the room naked so that her fattening could be observed, and would sleep on a bamboo bed which was thought to fatten her up. It was also meant to make it more possible for her to conceive easily.\n\nThis use for fertility purposes was also used at time for infertile wives and as a prerequisite for entrance into secret societies.<ref name=Brink>{{cite book|title=Social Aspects of Obesity|year=1995|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-2884491853|pages=71\u201384|author=Pamela J Brink|editor=I.De Garine and Nancy J. Pollock|chapter=Fertility and Fattening: the Annang Fattening Room}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Oral history===\nAccording to oral tradition, the Abiakpo came to the northern range of Anaang from Eka Abiakpo. They were quickly followed by the Ukana clan, the Utu, Ekpu, Ebom and Nyama (the [[British people|British]] lumped these groups together and gave them the name Otoro), and other Anaang clans. The Anaang and the entire people of Akwa Ibom and Cross River States of Nigeria (AkwaCross people) have occupied their land in the coastal Southeastern Nigeria for thousands of years.\n\nThe group is related to the [[Efik people|Efiks]] and the [[Ibibios]]. Migration brought the groups to live among the [[Akan people|Twi]] of [[Ghana]] where the name Anaang means \"fourth son\". From Ghana, the group moved eastward into present-day [[Cameroon]]. It was in the Cameroon highlands that the group broke off but later arrived at same territory in the Coastal Southeastern [[Nigeria]]. Lineages were recognized and the groups organized themselves into clans based on old family origins known as Iman, a similar structure extends into the land of their northern neighbors, the [[Igbo people|Igbo]].\n\n===Written history===\nVery little was written about the Anaang people before the mid-19th century. Early European traders who arrived in the cross river territories referred to groups who lived outside of the coastal areas as residents of Egbo-Sharry Country. The first written mention of the Anaangs is in [[Sigismund Koelle]]'s account of liberated slaves in [[Sierra Leone]]. He mentioned a liberated slave named ''Ebengo'' who hailed from Nkwot in [[Abak]]. Ebengo was captured and sold to the [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] but was subsequently freed by a British warship and later settled in [[Waterloo, Sierra Leone]]. The British soldiers listed the languages spoken by the slaves in that captured ship as \"Anaang\". The second mention is a description of what is known as the Ikot Udo Obong Wars. The British described the killings of the Anaangs by King ''Jaja'' of [[Opobo]] as a punishment for defying his orders and trading in palm oil directly with the British merchants instead of going through him as a middle man. In the war that ensued, the British intervened and with the help of the Anaangs, they captured King Jaja and exiled him to the [[West Indies]]. The British established a military post at [[Ikot Ekpene]] in 1904.\n\nFollowing [[British colonialism]] and with changes and ban in ancient hunting practices, the Anaang witnessed attacks by wild animals. As the men went to fight in [[World War II]] these attacks intensified. The British authorities called the attacks murder and blamed it on \"the barbarism of the Africans\". The Anaang were accused of belonging to a secret society called ''Ekpeowo'' ([[Leopard Society|The Human Leopards Society]]). It has been argued that killings born out of insurgency against the British elsewhere in Africa led to the branding of leopard attacks as murders by the British authorities among the Anaang. Between 1945 and 1948 about 196 people were killed in [[Ikot Okoro]] community in the present-day Oruk Anam LGA; the [[Ikot Okoro]] Police station was set up because of this reason. The British convicted 96 people and executed 77 innocent people. The Anaang religion called Idiong was banned and the priests arrested. Articles and worship materials were publicly burnt and those who did not convert to Christianity automatically became suspects.\n\nThe Anaangs have a history and reputation for fearlessness and the ability of villages and clans to bind together to fight a common enemy. This is perhaps why they were able to thrive living so close to the [[Aro Confederacy]]'s center, [[Arochukwu]] with its famed [[Ibini Ukpabi]] oracle. A particular interesting war group, or \"Warrior cult\", was the famous Oko warriors. This war group was highly functional in the 1950s. These warriors were considered invulnerable to penetration of knives, spears, and arrows. In various instances sharp machetes were tested on the body parts of members.\n\nThe Anaangs suffered [[genocide]] during the [[Nigerian Civil War]]. The war lasted for three years (1967\u20131970) and the Anaang lost a significant number of its people. The effect of the war and the resulting neglect of the Anaang is now a serious political issue and a source of unrest in the area.\n\n==Written language==\nParts of the [[Annang language]] may be intelligible to speakers of [[Efik language|Efik]], [[Ibibio language|Ibibio]], [[Oro language|Oron]], [[Eket]] (also known as [[Ekid]]) of the [[Akwa Akpa|Old Calabar Kingdom]]. Though the Anaang speech pattern was not written down, linguists have now produced an orthography of the language which makes it possible to produce written materials in the language (Idem-Agozino & Udondata, 2001).\nIn Annang dialect, the word \"ilung\"means village while in Ibibio it is called \" Idung\". The major linguistic difference between the Annang and other dialects is the predominant use of the letter \"L\" in place of \"r\" or \"d\",and the use of \"g\" in place of \"w\".The Annang dialect sounds hard but it is a dialect of freewill,ie the words roll out easily from your tongue than the Ibibio.\n\n==Demographics==\n*Nigeria\n**[[Akwa Ibom State]]\n**[[Cross River State]]\n**Benue (Efik-Ibibio people were the fourth largest ethnic group of the original settlers of Benue of Nigeria)\n*Equatorial Guinea (formerly [[Fernando Po (island)|Fernando Po]])\n*Cameroon\n*Ghana\n\nOverseas diaspora:{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n*Cuba\n*West Indies\n\n== Annang numbers ==\nNumbers from zero to ten:<ref>{{Cite books|url=https://www.amazon.com/%C3%91gwed-Ik%C3%B6-Anaa%C3%B1-Apa-ebook/dp/B01E1LDQLI/ref=sr_1_5?ie=UTF8&qid=1519178315&sr=8-5&keywords=ezekiel+ette|access-date= 12 October 2016|title=\u00d1gwed Ik\u00f6 Anaa\u00f1:: Apa \u00d1gwed 1}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!No. !! English !! Annang\n|-\n|0  || Zero || Ikpopo\n|-\n|1  || One || Ked \n|-\n|2  || Two || Iba\n|-\n|3  || Three || Ita\n|-\n|4  || Four  || Ina\u00f1\n|-\n|5  || Five || ition\n|-\n|6  || Six || Itioked\n|-\n|7  || Seven || Itiaba\n|-\n|8  || Eight || Itiaita\n|-\n|9  || Nine || Usoked\n|-\n|10 || Ten || duop\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n===Bibliography===\n*Brink, P. J. (1989) The Fattening Room among the Annang of Nigeria. Medical Anthropology 12 (1) p.&nbsp;131 - 143.\n*Ekanem, J. B. (2002) Clashing Cultures: Annang Not(with)standing Christianity: An Ethnography (Gods, Humans, and Religions, No. 3),  Peter Lang Publishing: Brussels. {{ISBN|0-8204-4687-4}}.\n*Enang, K. (1987) Some Key Religious concepts of the Annang. In Africana Marburgensia: Cross River Religion, Hackett, R. I. J. (ed) Sonderheft 12 (12) 21 \u2013 34.\n*Koelle, W. (1854) Polyglotta African Cited in Udo, E. U. (1983) The History of the Annang People, Apcon Press Ltd. Calabar, Nigeria.\n*Livingstone, W. P. (1916) Mary Slessor of Calabar: Pioneer Missionary, BiblioBazaar, {{ISBN|1-4264-3290-9}}.\n*Meek, C. K. (1937) Law and Authority in a Nigerian Tribe. Oxford, England. Oxford University Press {{ISBN|0-389-04031-2}}.\n*Noah, Monday Effiong (1988) Proceedings of the Ibibio Union 1928-1937.\n*{{cite book |author=Messenger, John Cowan |title=Anang Acculturation: A Study of Shifting Cultural Focus |year=1957| publisher= Ph.D Dissertation Northwestern University |location=Evanston, Illinois }}\n*Nair, Kaanan. K. (1972) Politics and society in South Eastern Nigeria, 1841\u20131906;: A study of power, diplomacy and commerce in Old Calabar (Cass library of African studies. General studies), London, Frank Cass, {{ISBN|0-7146-2296-6}}.\n*Pratten, D. (2007) The Man-Leopard Murders: History and Society in Colonial Nigeria. Indianapolis, Indiana University Press. {{ISBN|978-0-253-34956-9}}\nUdondata, J & Idem-Agozino, U. (2001) Annang Orthography, Uyo, Scholars Press.\n*Udo, E. U. (1983) The History of the Annang People, Calabar, Nigeria. Apcon Press Ltd.\n*Umoh, E. (2004) Annang Map with Boundaries, Plano TX. USA.\n*Waddell, H.M. (1893) Thirty Nine Years in West Africa and the West Indies. London. Frank Cass Ltd.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ikot Ekpene]]\n*[[Efik people]]\n*[[Ibibio people]]\n*[[Eket]]\n*[[Akwa Akpa]]\n*[[Ika-Annang]]\n*[[Ikom]]\n*[[Akamkpa]]\n*[[Bakassi]]\n*[[Ekpe]]\n*[[Nsibidi]]\n*[[Ekpo Masquerades|Ekpo Annang]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20111030123010/http://www.annangheritage.org/ Annang Heritage Organization]\n{{Ethnic groups in Nigeria}}\n\n[[Category:Annang]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Nigeria]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group = Anaang\n| total = 2.6 million\n| total_year = 2015\n| total_ref = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/anw|title=Anaang|website=[[Ethnologue]]|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n| regions = [[Akwa Ibom State]] ([[Nigeria]])\n| languages = [[Anaang language|Anaang]]\n| religions = [[Christianity]] and [[Paganism]]\n| related_groups = [[Ibibio people|Ibibio]], [[Efik people|Efik]]\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\nThe '''Anaang''' (also spelled '''Annang''') are a [[Nigeria|Southern Nigerian]] ethnic group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipobinusa.org/ourstory|title=Our Story|website=Indigenous People of Biafra USA|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> whose land is primarily within 8 of the present 31 [[Akwa Ibom State#Administrative areas|local government areas]] in [[Akwa Ibom State]]: [[Abak]], [[Essien Udim]], [[Etim Ekpo]], [[Ika, Nigeria|Ika]], [[Ikot Ekpene]], [[Obot Akara]], [[Oruk Anam]], [[Ukanafun]] in [[Akwa Ibom State]], and part of [[Obi Ngwa]]. They were formerly located in the former [[Abak]] and [[Ikot Ekpene]] Divisions of the Anaang Province, as well as part of the former [[Opobo]] Division of [[Uyo]] Province, in the former Eastern Region of Nigeria. The proper name for the [[Ika people|Ika]] of [[Akwa Ibom]] is [[Ika-Annang]].  Based on 2018 estimates, there are about 4 million Annang speakers in Akwa Ibom and over a million speakers living outside of the state including Nigeria.\n\n==Location==\nThe Anaang people are located in South [[Nigeria]] and specifically [[Akwa Ibom State]] and [[Cross River State]].  The political capital of the Anaang people is Ikot Ekpene Local Government Area. \n\n==Culture==\nAnaang society is [[patriarchal]]. Individuals locate their place in the social world from the ''Ilip'', literally translated as \"womb\". Thus a brother/sister from the same ''Ilip'' means that they can trace their origin to the same mother or father. Those who can so trace their ancestry to the same parents form ''Ufok'' (literally a house or compound). Several ''ufoks'' make up ''Ekpuks'' or [[extended family]] and several ''Ekpuks'' (extended families) make up \"Ilung\" (meaning village) and several villages make up the \"''abie''\" or clan. This is in many ways similar to the system used by other [[Biafra|Biafran]] peoples but more centralized<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Warrant_Chiefs_indirect_rule_in_sout.html?id=yYoKAQAAIAAJ|title=The Warrant Chiefs: indirect rule in southeastern Nigeria, 1891-1929|last=Afigbo|first=Adiele Eberechukwu|date=1972|publisher=Longman|language=en}}</ref>.\n\nLeadership at the family, lineage, village, or clan level remains the prerogative of the men, and lineage ties extends to women even after marriage. There are many societies and associations (''Ulim'' also called \"udim\") for men and women which are very important in traditional village life. Individuals are measured by both the number and types of memberships in ''Ulim'' and by the achievements of one or more ''Ulims''.  Governance is done by elderly males who act as the legislative arm called Afe Ichong, directed by the ''Abong Ichong'' (Village Chief and Clan Chief) who is the head and the chief executive but without the authority beyond what the ''Afe Ichong'' gives. A chief can be appointed by the ''Afe'' or can be an inherited office. \n\nThe Anang speak the [[Annang language]] and perform a masquerade after the yam harvest to mark the visit of ancestral spirits, or ''ekpo''. This is also the name of a men's associations that once had great influence among Ibibio groups. The Anang carve masks with grotesque features, known as ''iliok'', which are considered dangerous and may only be viewed by members of the ''ekpo''. Other masks embody the beautiful spirit, or ''mfon''.<ref name=\"masks\">{{Cite book|last1=Hahner-Herzog |first1=Iris |last2=Kecsk\u00e9si |first2=Maria |last3=Vajda |first3=L\u00e1szl\u00f3 |date=1998|title=African masks from the Barbier-Mueller Collection, Geneva|publisher=Prestel|location=Munich|isbn=978-3-7913-1806-6}}</ref>\n\nThe strength of any individual, family (or group for that matter) is typically based upon a consensus of the village or clan through this complex social system.  In all this, Anang women are not completely subordinate to men.  Instead Anaang women are partners and leaders in many aspects of Anaang tradition, including serving as female chief priests \"Abia Iyong\" in the Iyong cult or as healers in the healing cults.  The first-born female known as ''Aliaha'' is important and commands respect in the family and lineage.  Some traditions hold that a woman's first birth should take place in her mother's compound.  Women's organizations such as \"abi-de\" and \"Nyaama\", and \"Isong Iban\"  play important roles in giving the women voice and status in society. There are no traditional or cultural barriers that prevent women from attaining high offices or positions.\n\nAnaangs value the ability to speak well and oratory ability using [[proverb]]s is highly desirable, especially among the leaders. The American anthropologist, [[Peter Farb]], stated that the name \"Anaang\" among this group means \"they who speak well\". An individual who has the gift of eloquent speech is often complimented as ''Akwo Anaang'', meaning the \"Man of Anaang\".<ref>Farb, P. (1974) Word Play: What Happens when People Talk. New York. Alfred Knopf Publishers {{ISBN|0-679-73408-2}}.</ref>\n\n===Fattening room===\nThe fattening room is traditionally where virgin adolescent girls were fattened up in preparation for marriage. A fattening room girl is known as a ''mbobo''. This was an occasion for a major village celebration. As part of her preparation for marriage the girl was also instructed on how to be a wife. She would spend her time in the room naked so that her fattening could be observed, and would sleep on a bamboo bed which was thought to fatten her up. It was also meant to make it more possible for her to conceive easily.\n\nThis use for fertility purposes was also used at time for infertile wives and as a prerequisite for entrance into secret societies.<ref name=Brink>{{cite book|title=Social Aspects of Obesity|year=1995|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-2884491853|pages=71\u201384|author=Pamela J Brink|editor=I.De Garine and Nancy J. Pollock|chapter=Fertility and Fattening: the Annang Fattening Room}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Oral history===\nAccording to oral tradition, the Abiakpo came to the northern range of Anaang from Eka Abiakpo. They were quickly followed by the Ukana clan, the Utu, Ekpu, Ebom and Nyama (the [[British people|British]] lumped these groups together and gave them the name Otoro), and other Anaang clans. The Anaang and the entire people of Akwa Ibom and Cross River States of Nigeria (AkwaCross people) have occupied their land in the coastal Southeastern Nigeria for thousands of years.\n\nThe group is related to the [[Efik people|Efiks]] and the [[Ibibios]]. Migration brought the groups to live among the [[Akan people|Twi]] of [[Ghana]] where the name Anaang means \"fourth son\". From Ghana, the group moved eastward into present-day [[Cameroon]]. It was in the Cameroon highlands that the group broke off but later arrived at same territory in the Coastal Southeastern [[Nigeria]]. Lineages were recognized and the groups organized themselves into clans based on old family origins known as Iman, a similar structure extends into the land of their northern neighbors, the [[Igbo people|Igbo]].\n\n===Written history===\nVery little was written about the Anaang people before the mid-19th century. Early European traders who arrived in the cross river territories referred to groups who lived outside of the coastal areas as residents of Egbo-Sharry Country. The first written mention of the Anaangs is in [[Sigismund Koelle]]'s account of liberated slaves in [[Sierra Leone]]. He mentioned a liberated slave named ''Ebengo'' who hailed from Nkwot in [[Abak]]. Ebengo was captured and sold to the [[Portuguese people|Portuguese]] but was subsequently freed by a British warship and later settled in [[Waterloo, Sierra Leone]]. The British soldiers listed the languages spoken by the slaves in that captured ship as \"Anaang\". The second mention is a description of what is known as the Ikot Udo Obong Wars. The British described the killings of the Anaangs by King ''Jaja'' of [[Opobo]] as a punishment for defying his orders and trading in palm oil directly with the British merchants instead of going through him as a middle man. In the war that ensued, the British intervened and with the help of the Anaangs, they captured King Jaja and exiled him to the [[West Indies]]. The British established a military post at [[Ikot Ekpene]] in 1904.\n\nFollowing [[British colonialism]] and with changes and ban in ancient hunting practices, the Anaang witnessed attacks by wild animals. As the men went to fight in [[World War II]] these attacks intensified. The British authorities called the attacks murder and blamed it on \"the barbarism of the Africans\". The Anaang were accused of belonging to a secret society called ''Ekpeowo'' ([[Leopard Society|The Human Leopards Society]]). It has been argued that killings born out of insurgency against the British elsewhere in Africa led to the branding of leopard attacks as murders by the British authorities among the Anaang. Between 1945 and 1948 about 196 people were killed in [[Ikot Okoro]] community in the present-day Oruk Anam LGA; the [[Ikot Okoro]] Police station was set up because of this reason. The British convicted 96 people and executed 77 innocent people. The Anaang religion called Idiong was banned and the priests arrested. Articles and worship materials were publicly burnt and those who did not convert to Christianity automatically became suspects.\n\nThe Anaangs have a history and reputation for fearlessness and the ability of villages and clans to bind together to fight a common enemy. This is perhaps why they were able to thrive living so close to the [[Aro Confederacy]]'s center, [[Arochukwu]] with its famed [[Ibini Ukpabi]] oracle. A particular interesting war group, or \"Warrior cult\", was the famous Oko warriors. This war group was highly functional in the 1950s. These warriors were considered invulnerable to penetration of knives, spears, and arrows. In various instances sharp machetes were tested on the body parts of members.\n\nThe Anaangs suffered [[genocide]] during the [[Nigerian Civil War]]. The war lasted for three years (1967\u20131970) and the Anaang lost a significant number of its people. The effect of the war and the resulting neglect of the Anaang is now a serious political issue and a source of unrest in the area.\n\n==Written language==\nParts of the [[Annang language]] may be intelligible to speakers of [[Efik language|Efik]], [[Ibibio language|Ibibio]], [[Oro language|Oron]], [[Eket]] (also known as [[Ekid]]) of the [[Akwa Akpa|Old Calabar Kingdom]]. Though the Anaang speech pattern was not written down, linguists have now produced an orthography of the language which makes it possible to produce written materials in the language (Idem-Agozino & Udondata, 2001).\nIn Annang dialect, the word \"ilung\"means village while in Ibibio it is called \" Idung\". The major linguistic difference between the Annang and other dialects is the predominant use of the letter \"L\" in place of \"r\" or \"d\",and the use of \"g\" in place of \"w\".The Annang dialect sounds hard but it is a dialect of freewill,ie the words roll out easily from your tongue than the Ibibio.\n\n==Demographics==\n*Nigeria\n**[[Akwa Ibom State]]\n**[[Cross River State]]\n**Benue (Efik-Ibibio people were the fourth largest ethnic group of the original settlers of Benue of Nigeria)\n*Equatorial Guinea (formerly [[Fernando Po (island)|Fernando Po]])\n*Cameroon\n*Ghana\n\nOverseas diaspora:{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n*Cuba\n*West Indies\n\n== Annang numbers ==\nNumbers from zero to ten:<ref>{{Cite books|url=https://www.amazon.com/%C3%91gwed-Ik%C3%B6-Anaa%C3%B1-Apa-ebook/dp/B01E1LDQLI/ref=sr_1_5?ie=UTF8&qid=1519178315&sr=8-5&keywords=ezekiel+ette|access-date= 12 October 2016|title=\u00d1gwed Ik\u00f6 Anaa\u00f1:: Apa \u00d1gwed 1}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!No. !! English !! Annang\n|-\n|0  || Zero || Ikpopo\n|-\n|1  || One || Ked \n|-\n|2  || Two || Iba\n|-\n|3  || Three || Ita\n|-\n|4  || Four  || Ina\u00f1\n|-\n|5  || Five || ition\n|-\n|6  || Six || Itioked\n|-\n|7  || Seven || Itiaba\n|-\n|8  || Eight || Itiaita\n|-\n|9  || Nine || Usoked\n|-\n|10 || Ten || duop\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n===Bibliography===\n*Brink, P. J. (1989) The Fattening Room among the Annang of Nigeria. Medical Anthropology 12 (1) p.&nbsp;131 - 1