{cite web|url=http://samakal.com/bangladesh/article/18061063/%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A1%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%89%E0%A6%9C-%E0%A6%AC%E0%A6%A8%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A7%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B0-%E0%A6%A8%E0%A6%BF%E0%A6%B0%E0%A7%8D%E0%A6%A6%E0%A7%87%E0%A6%B6|title=\u09ac\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\u09a8\u09bf\u0989\u099c \u099f\u09cb\u09af\u09bc\u09c7\u09a8\u09cd\u099f\u09bf\u09ab\u09cb\u09b0 \u09a1\u099f\u0995\u09ae \u09ac\u09a8\u09cd\u09a7\u09c7\u09b0 \u09a8\u09bf\u09b0\u09cd\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6|publisher=}}</ref>\n| Bangladesh News 24 Hours Ltd.\n|[[Toufique Imrose Khalidi]]\n|-\n| {{Sort|Bangla News 24|''[[Banglanews24.com]]''}}\n| \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be \u09a8\u09bf\u0989\u099c \u09e8\u09ea\n| 1st June, 2010\n| [[East West Media Group]]\n| Juwel Mazhar \n|-\n| {{Sort|Priyo|''[[Priyo]]''}}\n| \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u09af\u09bc.\u0995\u09ae\n| 2011\n| \n|Zakaria Swapan\n|-\n| {{Sort|Risingbd.com|''[[Risingbd.com]]''}}\n| \u09b0\u09be\u0987\u099c\u09bf\u0982\u09ac\u09bf\u09a1\u09bf\n| 2013\n|Mohammad Nowsher Ali \n| Mohammad Nowsher Ali \n|-\n| {{Sort|Jagonews24.com|''[[Jagonews24.com]]''}}\n| \u099c\u09be\u0997\u09cb\u09a8\u09bf\u0989\u099c\u09e8\u09ea.\u0995\u09ae\n| 10 May 2014\n|AKC Private Limited\n|Mohiuddin Sarker\n|-\n| {{Sort|BBC Bangla|''[[BBC Bangla]]''}}\n| \u09ac\u09bf\u09ac\u09bf\u09b8\u09bf \u09ac\u09be\u0982\u09b2\u09be\n| 11 October 1941<ref name=\"About the BBC 2016\">{{cite web | title=BBC Bangla at 75: the digital future is now | website=About the BBC | date=2016-10-12 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/aboutthebbc/entries/8a7a57df-7790-4a1d-a414-d5576d4942c1 | access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref>\n| [[Broadcasting House]]\n| Sabir Mustafa<ref name=\"About the BBC 2016\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Monthly/weekly newspapers and magazines==\nMonthly Bandhan-construction, Real estate, Interior & Architecture related Popular Monthly Magazine\n* ''[[Forum (Bangladesh)|Forum]]'', a human rights oriented magazine published between 1969-1971, re-established in 2006\n* ''[[Dhaka Courier]]'', English-language news magazine founded in 1984, it is the longest running English current affairs magazine in the country.\n* ''[[Holiday (newspaper)|Holiday]]'', an English-language weekly newspaper<ref name=growth2012 />\n* ''[[Ice Today|ICE Today]]'', an English-language fashion and lifestyle magazine\n* ''[[Weekly Blitz]]'', an English-language tabloid weekly founded in 2003 and edited by [[Salah Choudhury]]<ref name=growth2012>{{cite news |title=Blitz emerges as one of the fastest growing newspapers in Bangladesh |url=http://www.weeklyblitz.net/2711/blitz-emerges-as-one-of-the-fastest-growing |work=Weekly Blitz |date=2012-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127024513/http://www.weeklyblitz.net/2711/blitz-emerges-as-one-of-the-fastest-growing |archive-date=2013-01-27 |accessdate=2013-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Sohail |last=Choudhury |date=2013-03-15 |title=Not Only God, Fear us Too! |url=http://www.sunofindia.com/not-only-god-fear-us-too/ |newspaper=Sun of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215139/http://www.sunofindia.com/not-only-god-fear-us-too/ |archive-date=2013-10-04 |accessdate=2013-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==News agencies==\nBefore 1972, news agencies in Bangladesh were local branches of international [[news agency|agencies]].\n* [[Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha]] (BSS), the official [[state media|government-owned]] news agency of Bangladesh, was created on 1 January 1972 from the Dhaka bureau of the state-owned. [[Abul Kalam Azad (journalist)|Abul Kalam Azad]], who was formerly Prime Minister [[Sheikh Hasina]]'s press secretary, became its chief editor in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bssnews.net/md-profile.php|title=Managing Director and Chief Editor's Profile|website=Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha|access-date=2016-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180522133903/http://bssnews.net/md-profile.php|archive-date=2018-05-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*[[Associated Press of Pakistan]] (APP) (no relation to [[Associated Press]] (AP)). It exchanges news with [[Press Trust of India]] (PTI) and other foreign agencies.<ref name=\"growth2012\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bssnews.net/bss-profile.php |title=BSS Profile |website=Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha |access-date=2016-01-29}}</ref> \n* [[United News of Bangladesh]] (UNB) is a private news agency in service since 1988. It partners with AP, [[United News of India]] (UNI), and other foreign agencies.<ref name=growth2012 /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unbnews.org/smartnews/unbsite.nsf/$all/8D891695EBC78E5D65256E980034F04C?OpenDocument&HomePage |title=About-UNB |website=United News of Bangladesh |access-date=2016-01-29}}</ref>\n\n==Defunct newspapers==\n* ''[[Ajker Kagoj]]'' ({{lang-bn|\u09a6\u09c8\u09a8\u09bf\u0995 \u0986\u099c\u0995\u09c7\u09b0 \u0995\u09be\u0997\u099c}}; \"Today's Paper\"), a Bengali-language newspaper published in the modern approach between 1991-2007\n* ''[[Amar Desh]]'' ({{lang-bn|\u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u09a6\u09c7\u09b6}}; \"My country\"), a Bengali-language newspaper published between 2004-2013<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bangla.bdnews24.com/bangladesh/article612746.bdnews?playVideo=true|title=\u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u09a6\u09c7\u09b6\u09c7\u09b0 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09b8 \u2018\u09ac\u09a8\u09cd\u09a7\u2019|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.ittefaq.com.bd/index.php?ref=MjBfMDRfMTJfMTNfMV8xXzFfMzMxODI=|title=\u0986\u09ae\u09be\u09b0 \u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 \u09aa\u09a4\u09cd\u09b0\u09bf\u0995\u09be \u09ac\u09a8\u09cd\u09a7 :: \u09a6\u09c8\u09a8\u09bf\u0995 \u0987\u09a4\u09cd\u09a4\u09c7\u09ab\u09be\u0995|first=The Daily|last=Ittefaq|work=archive.ittefaq.com.bd}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Bangladesh Observer]]'', an English-language daily published between 1949-2010 and last edited by [[Iqbal Sobhan Chowdhury]]<ref name=listof2010editors />\n* ''[[Kishore Bangla]]'', a Bengali juvenile weekly published between 1977-1983\n* [[Banglar Bani]], Bengali Language newspaper with a Pro Bangladesh Awami League ideology.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Media of Bangladesh]]\n* [[Communications in Bangladesh]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Newspapers in Bangladesh}}\n{{Media of Bangladesh}}\n{{Lists of newspapers in Asia}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of newspapers by country|Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Bangladesh| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of Bangladeshi media|Newspapers]]\n", "name_user": "Ashait", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOnline newspapers and portals", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_newspapers_in_Bangladesh"}
{"title_page": "Nazneen", "text_new": "{{for|the given name|Nazneen (given name)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Nazneen\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Nazneen\n| birth_date    =  <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = [[Kolkata]], [[India]]\n| death_date    =  <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Indian\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Actress\n| years_active  = 1972 \u20131990\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = ''[[Sa-Re-Ga-Ma-Pa]]''<br>''[[Chalte Chalte (1976 film)|Chalte Chalte]]''<br>''[[Mahabharat (1988 TV series)|Mahabharat]]''\n}}\n\n'''Nazneen''' is an Indian Bollywood actress who was active in the 1970s and 1980s. She was born on (23 February 1958) in [[Kolkata]] and studied in [[Lucknow]] before moving to [[Mumbai]] with her parents. She was cast in ''[[Sa-Re-Ga-Ma-Pa]]'' (1972) after meeting an assistant to director [[Satyen Bose]] at a party. She subsequently played in the hit movies ''[[Kora Kagaz]]'' (1974), ''[[Chalte Chalte (1976 film)|Chalte Chalte]]'' (1976) and ''[[Dildaar]]'' (1977).<ref>{{cite book|author=T.M. Ramachandran |title=Film World Volume 14 |year=1978}}</ref>\nNazneen starred in the hit television series Mahabharat produced by B.R Chopra as Kunti who was the mother of the Pandavas.\n\n==Early life==\nNazneen was born into a Muslim family. Her father owned a printing press. She did her schooling from Hill Grange High School.<ref name=\"nazneen\">[http://cineplot.com/nazneen-interview/ Nazneen - Interview I (1976) on Cineplot]</ref> Actress [[Neetu Singh]] went to the same school as she. Neetu would invite her to her mother\u2019s flat for lunch.<ref name=\"neetu\">[http://cineplot.com/nazneen-interview-ii/ Nazneen - Interview II (1978) on Cineplot]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAt a party hosted by a relative of hers, producer Yusuf Teendarwajawalla, who made ''[[Mere Humsafar]]'' (1970), and director [[Satyen Bose]] offered her a role in ''[[Sa-Re-Ga-Ma-Pa]]'' (1972), which he directed.<ref name=\"nazneen\"/>\n\nNazneen was signed for two more films to be directed by Satyen Bose but they were never made. But working under the veteran director did help her a lot. Satyen Bose also wanted Nazneen to have a screen name. He had suggested Suparna, and then somebody suggested Sonali. However, she chose to be herself, Nazneen.<ref name=\"nazneen\"/>\n\nIn 1974 she acted in ''[[Kora Kagaz]]'', which won her critical acclaim. In the film she played  [[Jaya Bachchan]]'s sister. After ''Kora Kaagaz'' she got several offers, but everyone said \u201cthere was a wonderful role of a sister\u201d. \u201cThey all thought I was good only for goody-goody roles\u201d, Nazneen said in an interview conducted in 1976.<ref name=\"nazneen\"/>\n\nNazneen declined all those offers. She was already playing the leading lady in a few \"B\" class films and the producers of these films told Nazneen if she accepted the sisters\u2019 roles their films would suffer at the box office.<ref name=\"nazneen\"/>\n\n== Filmography ==\n*''[[Sa-Re-Ga-Ma-Pa]]'' (1972)\n*''[[Mere Garib Nawaz]]'' (1973)\n*''[[Nirdosh (1973 film)|Nirdosh]]'' (1973)\n*''[[Kora Kagaz]]'' (1974)\n*''[[Ranga Khush]]'' (1975)\n*''[[Chalte Chalte (1976 film)|Chalte Chalte]]'' (1976)\n*''[[Fauji (1976 film)|Fauji]]'' (1976)\n*''[[Yaari Zindabad]]'' (1976)\n*''[[Chaalu Mera Naam]]'' (1977)\n*''[[Dildaar]]'' (1977)\n*''[[Haiwan]]'' (1977)\n*''[[Bin Phere Hum Tere]]'' (1979)\n*''[[Adventures of Aladdin]]'' (1979)\n*''[[Oh Bewafaa]]'' (1980)\n*''[[Ek Duuje Ke Liye]]'' (1981)\n*''[[Ek Hi Bhool]]'' (1981)\n*''[[Khuda Kasam (1981 film)|Khuda Kasam]]'' (1981)\n*Waqt ki Dewar (1981)\n*''[[Chambal Ke Daku]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Do Ustad]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Shekhar Mera Naam]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Aadamkhor]]'' (1986)\nNazneen also played the role of \"Kunti\" (mother of Karna and the Pandava brothers) in the 1988 TV serial ''[[Mahabharat (1988 TV series)|Mahabharat]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cineplot.com/nazneen/ |title=Nazneen \u2013 Profile |website=cineplot.com |accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:20th-century Indian actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the given name|Nazneen (given name)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Nazneen\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Nazneen\n| birth_date    =  <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = [[Kolkata]], [[India]]\n| death_date    =  <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Indian\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Actress\n| years_active  = 1972 \u20131990\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = ''[[Sa-Re-Ga-Ma-Pa]]''<br>''[[Chalte Chalte (1976 film)|Chalte Chalte]]''<br>''[[Mahabharat (1988 TV series)|Mahabharat]]''\n}}\n\n'''Nazneen''' is an Indian Bollywood actress who was active in the 1970s and 1980s. She was born on (23 Febuary 1958) in [[Kolkata]] and studied in [[Lucknow]] before moving to [[Mumbai]] with her parents. She was cast in ''[[Sa-Re-Ga-Ma-Pa]]'' (1972) after meeting an assistant to director [[Satyen Bose]] at a party. She subsequently played in the hit movies ''[[Kora Kagaz]]'' (1974), ''[[Chalte Chalte (1976 film)|Chalte Chalte]]'' (1976) and ''[[Dildaar]]'' (1977).<ref>{{cite book|author=T.M. Ramachandran |title=Film World Volume 14 |year=1978}}</ref>\nNazneen starred in the hit television series Mahabharat produced by B.R Chopra as Kunti who was the mother of the Pandavas.\n\n==Early life==\nNazneen was born into a Muslim family. Her father owned a printing press. She did her schooling from Hill Grange High School.<ref name=\"nazneen\">[http://cineplot.com/nazneen-interview/ Nazneen - Interview I (1976) on Cineplot]</ref> Actress [[Neetu Singh]] went to the same school as she. Neetu would invite her to her mother\u2019s flat for lunch.<ref name=\"neetu\">[http://cineplot.com/nazneen-interview-ii/ Nazneen - Interview II (1978) on Cineplot]</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAt a party hosted by a relative of hers, producer Yusuf Teendarwajawalla, who made ''[[Mere Humsafar]]'' (1970), and director [[Satyen Bose]] offered her a role in ''[[Sa-Re-Ga-Ma-Pa]]'' (1972), which he directed.<ref name=\"nazneen\"/>\n\nNazneen was signed for two more films to be directed by Satyen Bose but they were never made. But working under the veteran director did help her a lot. Satyen Bose also wanted Nazneen to have a screen name. He had suggested Suparna, and then somebody suggested Sonali. However, she chose to be herself, Nazneen.<ref name=\"nazneen\"/>\n\nIn 1974 she acted in ''[[Kora Kagaz]]'', which won her critical acclaim. In the film she played  [[Jaya Bachchan]]'s sister. After ''Kora Kaagaz'' she got several offers, but everyone said \u201cthere was a wonderful role of a sister\u201d. \u201cThey all thought I was good only for goody-goody roles\u201d, Nazneen said in an interview conducted in 1976.<ref name=\"nazneen\"/>\n\nNazneen declined all those offers. She was already playing the leading lady in a few \"B\" class films and the producers of these films told Nazneen if she accepted the sisters\u2019 roles their films would suffer at the box office.<ref name=\"nazneen\"/>\n\n== Filmography ==\n*''[[Sa-Re-Ga-Ma-Pa]]'' (1972)\n*''[[Mere Garib Nawaz]]'' (1973)\n*''[[Nirdosh (1973 film)|Nirdosh]]'' (1973)\n*''[[Kora Kagaz]]'' (1974)\n*''[[Ranga Khush]]'' (1975)\n*''[[Chalte Chalte (1976 film)|Chalte Chalte]]'' (1976)\n*''[[Fauji (1976 film)|Fauji]]'' (1976)\n*''[[Yaari Zindabad]]'' (1976)\n*''[[Chaalu Mera Naam]]'' (1977)\n*''[[Dildaar]]'' (1977)\n*''[[Haiwan]]'' (1977)\n*''[[Bin Phere Hum Tere]]'' (1979)\n*''[[Adventures of Aladdin]]'' (1979)\n*''[[Oh Bewafaa]]'' (1980)\n*''[[Ek Duuje Ke Liye]]'' (1981)\n*''[[Ek Hi Bhool]]'' (1981)\n*''[[Khuda Kasam (1981 film)|Khuda Kasam]]'' (1981)\n*Waqt ki Dewar (1981)\n*''[[Chambal Ke Daku]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Do Ustad]]'' (1982)\n*''[[Shekhar Mera Naam]]'' (1983)\n*''[[Aadamkhor]]'' (1986)\nNazneen also played the role of \"Kunti\" (mother of Karna and the Pandava brothers) in the 1988 TV serial ''[[Mahabharat (1988 TV series)|Mahabharat]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cineplot.com/nazneen/ |title=Nazneen \u2013 Profile |website=cineplot.com |accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:20th-century Indian actresses]]\n", "name_user": "S.Didam", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nazneen"}
